  1633Ôćĺ### Testing
  1635Ôćĺ`Result` instances have two unsafe methods, aptly called `_unsafeUnwrap` and `_unsafeUnwrapErr` which **should only be used in a test environment**.
  1636Ôćĺ
  1637Ôćĺ`_unsafeUnwrap` takes a `Result<T, E>` and returns a `T` when the result is an `Ok`, otherwise it throws a custom object.
  1638Ôćĺ
  1639Ôćĺ`_unsafeUnwrapErr` takes a `Result<T, E>` and returns a `E` when the result is an `Err`, otherwise it throws a custom object.
  1640Ôćĺ
  1641ÔćĺThat way you can do something like:
  1642Ôćĺ
  1643Ôćĺ```typescript
  1644Ôćĺexpect(myResult._unsafeUnwrap()).toBe(someExpectation)
  1645Ôćĺ```
  1646Ôćĺ
  1647ÔćĺHowever, do note that `Result` instances are comparable. So you don't necessarily need to unwrap them in order to assert expectations in your tests. So you could also do something like this:
  1648Ôćĺ
  1649Ôćĺ```typescript
  1650Ôćĺimport { ok } from 'neverthrow'
  1651Ôćĺ
  1652Ôćĺ// ...
  1653Ôćĺ
  1654Ôćĺexpect(callSomeFunctionThatReturnsAResult("with", "some", "args")).toEqual(ok(someExpectation));
  1655Ôćĺ```
  1656Ôćĺ
  1657ÔćĺBy default, the thrown value does not contain a stack trace. This is because stack trace generation [makes error messages in Jest harder to understand](https://github.com/supermacro/neverthrow/pull/215). If you want stack traces to be generated, call `_unsafeUnwrap` and / or `_unsafeUnwrapErr` with a config object:
  1658Ôćĺ
  1659Ôćĺ```typescript
  1660Ôćĺ_unsafeUnwrapErr({
  1661Ôćĺ  withStackTrace: true,
  1662Ôćĺ})
  1663Ôćĺ
  1664Ôćĺ// ^ Now the error object will have a `.stack` property containing the current stack
  1665Ôćĺ```
  1666Ôćĺ
  1667Ôćĺ---
  1668Ôćĺ
  1669ÔćĺIf you find this package useful, please consider [sponsoring me](https://github.com/sponsors/supermacro/) or simply [buying me a coffee](https://ko-fi.com/gdelgado)!
  1670Ôćĺ
  1671Ôćĺ---
  1672Ôćĺ
  1673Ôćĺ## A note on the Package Name
  1675ÔćĺAlthough the package is called `neverthrow`, please don't take this literally. I am simply encouraging the developer to think a bit more about the ergonomics and usage of whatever software they are writing.
  1676Ôćĺ
  1677Ôćĺ`Throw`ing and `catching` is very similar to using `goto` statements - in other words; it makes reasoning about your programs harder. Secondly, by using `throw` you make the assumption that the caller of your function is implementing `catch`. This is a known source of errors. Example: One dev `throw`s and another dev uses the function without prior knowledge that the function will throw. Thus, and edge case has been left unhandled and now you have unhappy users, bosses, cats, etc.
  1678Ôćĺ
  1679ÔćĺWith all that said, there are definitely good use cases for throwing in your program. But much less than you might think.
  1680Ôćĺ
  1681Ôćĺ### License
  1683ÔćĺThe neverthrow project is available as open source under the terms of the [MIT license](https://github.com/supermacro/neverthrow/blob/master/LICENSE).
